GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 2
HOUSE BILL 763
Committee Substitute Favorable 4/29/25
Short Title: Neighbor State License Recognition Act. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
April 7, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO PROVIDE FOR OCCUPATIONAL LICENSURE RECOGNITION FOR
3 INDIVIDUALS LICENSED IN CERTAIN NEIGHBORING STATES WHO ESTABLISH
4 RESIDENCE IN THIS STATE.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1. Chapter 93B of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
7 section to read:
8 "§ 93B-15.3. Licensure recognition for individuals licensed in neighboring states.
9 (a) Applicability. – This section applies to all occupational licensing boards and State
10 agency licensing boards except as provided in this subsection. This section shall not apply to:
11 (1) Licensure of any healthcare practitioner licensed under Chapter 90 of the
12 General Statutes.
13 (2) Veterinarians licensed under Article 11 of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes.
14 (3) Admission to the practice of law or licensure as an attorney under Chapter 84
15 of the General Statutes.
16 (b) Licensure Recognition. – Notwithstanding any other provision of law, an
17 occupational licensing board or a State agency licensing board subject to this section shall issue
18 a license, certification, or registration to any applicant who establishes residence in this State and
19 satisfies all of the following conditions:
20 (1) The applicant is currently licensed, certified, or registered in Georgia, South
21 Carolina, Tennessee, Virginia, or West Virginia in the discipline applied for
22 in this State at the same or substantially equivalent practice level, as
23 determined by the occupational licensing board or State agency licensing
24 board.
25 (2) The applicant has been licensed, certified, or registered in one or more of the
26 states listed in subdivision (1) of this subsection for at least one year.
27 (3) The applicant has passed an examination required for the license, certification,
28 or registration in the jurisdiction in which the applicant holds a current license,
29 certification, or registration, if an examination was required.
30 (4) The applicant is in good standing in all jurisdictions within the United States
31 in which the applicant holds or has ever held a license, certification, or
32 registration in the profession for which the applicant is seeking licensure,
33 certification, or registration in this State.
34 (5) The applicant has not voluntarily surrendered a license, certification, or
35 registration or had a license, certification, or registration revoked in any
36 jurisdiction within the United States as a result of unprofessional conduct
*H763-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 related to the profession for which the applicant is seeking licensure,
2 certification, or registration in this State.
3 (6) The applicant demonstrates competency in the profession through methods
4 determined by the board, which may include having met the minimum
5 education, clinical supervision, or work experience requirements in effect in
6 the originating state at the time the applicant obtained the license, certification,
7 or registration from that state.
8 (7) The applicant does not have any active or pending disciplinary actions from
9 an occupational licensing board or agency in another jurisdiction within the
10 United States, and, if applicable, the occupational licensing board or State
11 agency licensing board has completed verification under subsection (c) of this
12 section.
13 (8) The applicant does not have a disqualifying criminal history record, as
14 determined by the occupational licensing board or State agency licensing
15 board under G.S. 93B-8.1 and related provisions of law.
16 (9) The applicant has paid all applicable fees, including fees for application
17 processing, license issuance, verification of credentials, and background
18 checks.
19 (c) Prior Disciplinary Actions. – If the applicant has any prior resolved disciplinary
20 actions from an occupational licensing board or State agency licensing board at the time of
21 application, the occupational licensing board or State agency licensing board to which the
22 applicant is applying shall determine and verify that the disciplinary action is resolved and, if
23 applicable, corrective action has been taken. If a disciplinary action is pending in another
24 jurisdiction, an occupational licensing board or State agency licensing board shall suspend the
25 application process for any license, certificate, or registration under this section until the
26 disciplinary action has been resolved.
27 (d) Required Information. – Each occupational licensing board or State agency licensing
28 board shall publish a document that lists the specific criteria or requirements for licensure,
29 certification, or registration by the board under this section and any necessary documentation
30 needed for satisfying the requirements. The information required by this subsection shall be
31 published on the occupational licensing board's or State agency licensing board's website.
32 (e) Effect on Other Agreements. – Nothing in this section shall be construed to prevent
33 any occupational licensing board or State agency licensing board in this State from entering into
34 a reciprocity agreement with another jurisdiction or to invalidate any existing reciprocity
35 agreement between any occupational licensing board or agency in this State and another
36 jurisdiction.
37 (f) Scope of License. – Any license, certification, or registration granted by an
38 occupational licensing board or State agency licensing board to any applicant under this section
39 shall be valid only in this State and does not extend validity to other jurisdictions, including
40 through an interstate compact, unless otherwise provided by law or interstate agreement.
41 (g) Rights and Obligations. – Any individual who is licensed, certified, or registered
42 under this section shall be entitled to the same rights and subject to the same obligations as
43 required of an individual who was licensed, certified, or registered by an occupational licensing
44 board or State agency licensing board in this State under any other provision of law.
45 (h) Alternative Pathway. – Nothing in this section shall be construed to prohibit an
46 individual from proceeding under the existing licensure, certification, or registration
47 requirements established by an occupational licensing board or State agency licensing board in
48 this State."
49 SECTION 2. Report. – Beginning on October 31, 2026, each occupational licensing
50 board and State agency licensing board subject to G.S. 93B-15.3, as enacted by this act, shall
51 include all of the following data for the previous fiscal year in the annual report to the Secretary
Page 2 House Bill 763-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 of State, the Attorney General, and the Joint Legislative Administrative Procedure Oversight
2 Committee, as required by G.S. 93B-2:
3 (1) The number of individuals who applied for licensure, certification, or
4 registration in accordance with G.S. 93B-15.3.
5 (2) The number of individuals who received licensure, certification, or
6 registration in accordance with G.S. 93B-15.3.
7 (3) The number of individuals who were denied licensure, certification, or
8 registration in accordance with G.S. 93B-15.3, including the reasons for
9 denial.
10 SECTION 3. Effective Date. – This act becomes effective October 1, 2025, and
11 applies to applications for licensure, certification, or registration received on or after that date.
